---- ALGORITHMS ----

>> A2: Briefly describe how you implemented argument parsing.  How do
>> you arrange for the elements of argv[] to be in the right order?
>> How do you avoid overflowing the stack page?

I tokenize the command line by spaces using strtok_r, store pointers in argv[], 
and then push the arguments onto the user stack in reverse order so they appear 
in the correct order when accessed. I align the stack to 4 bytes, add a null sentinel, 
then push the argv pointers, argc, and a fake return address. To avoid overflow, 
I build everything within a single zeroed stack page and check that each push stays
within the page boundary.

---- RATIONALE ----

>> A3: Why does Pintos implement strtok_r() but not strtok()?
 Pintos uses strtok_r() because it is re entry and thread-safe, 
 meaning it can safely parse strings in multiple threads without interfering 
 with each other. The regular strtok() uses static internal state, 
 which would break in a multi-threaded kernel like Pintos.



>> A4: In Pintos, the kernel separates commands into a executable name
>> and arguments.  In Unix-like systems, the shell does this
>> separation.  Identify at least two advantages of the Unix approach.

 The Unix approach is better because (1) it keeps the kernel simpler and smaller, 
 leaving command parsing to user programs, and (2) it allows different shells or 
 interpreters to implement their own parsing rules or features without changing the kernel.

